oks to the STEM fields as a case study, where gendered cultures and structures in academia have contributed to an underrepresentation of women. While some have approached underrepresentation as a national concern with a national solution, Zippel highlights how gender relations are reconfigured in global academia. For U.S. women in particular, international collaboration offers opportunities to step outside of exclusionary networks at home. International collaboration is not the panacea to gendered inequalities in academia, but, as Zippel argues, international considerations can be key to ending the steady attrition of women in STEM fields and developing a more inclusive academic world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCareer developmentxUnited States. 0aCareer developmentzUnited States. 0aCareer development. 0aSciencexInternational cooperationxUnited States. 0aSciencexInternational cooperation. 0aScience. 0aWomen in sciencexUnited States. 0aWomen in sciencezUnited States. 0aWomen in science. 0aWomen scientistsxUnited States. 0aWomen scientistszUnited States. 0aWomen scientists. 4aacademic. 4acollaboration/international collaboration/networks. 4agender equality/equal opportunity. 4agender. 4ainternational research. 4aprofession/faculty/academics/professors/researchers. 4auniversity/academia/higher education. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360150540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503601505423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503601505.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles